questions.scenario:
You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput microservice is experiencing a gradual memory leak, eventually leading to an `OutOfMemoryError: Java heap space`. Your team suspects a custom session cache. Here is the implementation snippet:

java
@Service
public class ClientSessionManager {
    private final Map<ClientToken, SessionContext> sessionCache = new WeakHashMap<>();

    public synchronized void registerSession(String tokenStr, SessionContext context) {
        ClientToken token = new ClientToken(tokenStr);
        context.setToken(token); 
        sessionCache.put(token, context);
    }
}


The profiling dumps show that `ClientToken` objects are never garbage collected, even after clients disconnect and all external references to the tokens are dropped.

You are debugging a production issue where a highly concurrent financial ledger service experiences severe thread contention and sporadic JVM-level deadlocks. The application is running within a Spring Boot container, and threads lock keys dynamically inside a Spring `@Transactional` block using a custom nested locking structure on a `ConcurrentHashMap`:

java
@Service
public class LedgerService {
    private final ConcurrentHashMap<String, Account> accounts = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

    @Transactional
    public void transferFunds(String fromId, String toId, BigDecimal amount) {
        accounts.compute(fromId, (fromKey, fromAcc) -> {
            accounts.compute(toId, (toKey, toAcc) -> {
                fromAcc.withdraw(amount);
                toAcc.deposit(amount);
                return toAcc;
            });
            return fromAcc;
        });
    }
}


Thread dumps during peak hours show multiple application threads in `BLOCKED` states at `java.util.concurrent.ConcurrentHashMap.compute`.
